Claim 1: For any $f\in \mathcal{H}$, there is $m_\epsilon\in \mathbb{Z}^{N(\epsilon)}$, such that \begin{align*} \Phi_\epsilon(m_\epsilon)\rightarrow \Phi(f),\quad \text{as $\epsilon\rightarrow 0$}. \end{align*}
Proof: Since $f\in \mathcal{H}\subset L^2[0,1]$, it can be uniformly approximated by a rational valued simple function. Without loss of generality, we assume $f$ is a rational valued simple function, and define it as \begin{align} f(\eta)=p_\sigma+\frac{\alpha_\sigma}{d_\sigma},\quad \eta \in (\xi_\sigma,\xi_{\sigma+1}),\quad \sigma=1,…,M, \end{align} where $(0,1]=\bigsqcup_{\sigma=1}^M(\xi_\sigma,\xi_{\sigma+1}]$, and $p_\sigma,0\leq \alpha_\sigma&lt;d_\sigma$ are all integers. For such $f$, and fix $\epsilon$, we construct the vector in $\mathbb{Z}^{N(\epsilon)}$ as follows: \begin{align} m_j=\begin{cases} p_\sigma+1 \text{ at the first $\alpha$ indices of $J_\sigma$},\\ p_\sigma \text{ at the next $d_\sigma-\alpha$ indices of $J_\sigma$}, \end{cases} \end{align} where the index set $J_\sigma=\{j|\eta_j\in (\xi_\sigma,\xi_{\sigma+1})\}.$ Now we construct a function $f_\epsilon$ in the following way: \begin{align} f_\epsilon(\eta)=m_j,\quad \eta\in [\frac{1}{2}(\eta_{j+1}+\eta_{j}),\frac{1}{2}(\eta_j+\eta_{j-1})). \end{align} Then, one can show that \begin{align} f_\epsilon\rightarrow f,\quad \text{weakly}\quad as \quad \epsilon\downarrow 0. \end{align} That is to say \begin{align} \int_{0}^1f_\epsilon(\eta) d\mu(\eta)\rightarrow\int_0^1 f(\eta)d\mu(\eta). \end{align} In fact, by linearity of Lebesgue integral, we have \begin{align} \int_0^1f_\epsilon(\eta)d\mu(\eta)&amp;=\sum_{\sigma=1}^M\int_{\xi_\sigma}^{\xi_{\sigma+1}}f_\epsilon(\eta)d\mu(\eta)\\ &amp;\sim_{\epsilon\downarrow 0}\sum_{\sigma=1}^M \left((1+p_\sigma)\frac{\alpha_\sigma}{d_\sigma}+p_\sigma\frac{d_\sigma-\alpha_\sigma}{d_\sigma}\right)\mu([\xi_\sigma,\xi_{\sigma+1}])\\ &amp;=\sum_{\sigma=1}^M \left(\frac{\alpha_\sigma}{d_\sigma}+p_\sigma\right)\mu([\xi_\sigma,\xi_{\sigma+1}])\\ &amp;=\int_0^1 f(\eta)d\mu(\eta). \end{align} Then one can easily show that \begin{align} \Phi_\epsilon(m)\rightarrow\Phi(f_\epsilon). \end{align}
Now, if we set $f^*$ to be the (unique) minimizer of $\min_{f\in\mathcal{H}}\Phi(f)$, then by claim 1, we can find a sequence of $\Phi_\epsilon(m_\epsilon)$, such that
\begin{align} \lim_{\epsilon \downarrow 0}\Phi_\epsilon(m_\epsilon)=\Phi(f^*). \end{align}
Meanwhile, for any $\epsilon$, if $\Phi_\epsilon(m)$ assumes minimum at $m^*_\epsilon$, then we have
\begin{align} \lim_{\epsilon\downarrow 0}\Phi_\epsilon(m^*_\epsilon)\leq \Phi(f^*), \end{align}
in other words, we have
\begin{align} \lim_{\epsilon\downarrow 0}\left(\min_{m\in \mathbb{Z}^{N(\epsilon)}}\Phi_\epsilon(m)\right)\leq \min_{f\in \mathcal{H}}\Phi(f). \label{leq} \end{align}
Claim 2: For any $m_\epsilon\in \mathbb{Z}^{N(\epsilon)}$, there is $f_\epsilon\in \mathcal{H}$, such that \begin{align} \liminf_{\epsilon\downarrow 0}\left(\Phi_{\epsilon}(m_\epsilon)-\Phi(f_\epsilon)\right)\geq 0. \end{align}
